  "answer": "**This specific argument—modeling moral and legislative sciences on the methods of Adam Smith and J.-B. Say in political economy, while treating laws and institutions as facts to be observed rather than systems to be invented—is not present in the Falsafa corpus.**\n\nExtensive searches across the English translations for phrases like \"Adam Smith,\" \"J.-B. Say,\" \"Jean-Baptiste Say,\" \"political economy\" (with or without Smith/Say), \"legislative science,\" \"moral science,\" and key conceptual terms like \"laws\" \"institutions\" \"observed\" \"invented\" returned zero results. The corpus contains relevant works on legislation and political theory, such as Charles Comte's *Traité de Législation* (Vols. I–IV) and *Traité de la Propriété* (Vols. I–II), and Charles Dunoyer's *Nouveau traité d'économie* (Vols. I–II), which discuss laws, institutions, morality, and economy from a liberal perspective.[^1] However, no passages name Smith or Say in this connection, nor match the described methodological claim.\n\n[^1]: From `list_works` results listing these works by author \"comte\" and full corpus scan.",
